5|$|Saint Paul has a {{continental}} climate {{typical of the}} Upper Midwestern United States. Winters are frigid and snowy, while summers are warm to hot and humid. On the Köppen climate classification, Saint Paul falls in the hot summer humid continental climate zone (Dfa). The city experiences {{a full range of}} precipitation and related <b>weather</b> <b>events,</b> including snow, sleet, ice, rain, thunderstorms, tornadoes, and fog.|$|E
5|$|The most {{destructive}} of the <b>weather</b> <b>events,</b> an EF4 tornado, traveled {{for nearly an}} hour through four counties in Oklahoma during the evening of February10. It destroyed 114residences in Lone Grove alone. All casualties (8 deaths and 46 injuries) from the outbreak were due to the tornado in the Lone Grove area in Carter County. It was the deadliest tornado to hit Oklahoma since May3, 1999 and the strongest tornado during the month of February in Oklahoma since 1950.|$|E
