50|$|The 2006 Central Pacific cyclone, {{also known}} as 91C.INVEST or Storm 91C, was an unusual <b>weather</b> <b>event</b> of 2006. Forming on October 30, from a {{mid-latitude}} cyclone in the north Pacific mid-latitudes, it moved over waters warmer than normal. The system acquired some features more typical of subtropical or even tropical cyclones. However, as it neared western North America it fell apart. Moisture from its remains then caused substantial rainfall in British Columbia. The exact status and nature of this <b>weather</b> <b>event</b> is unknown, with meteorologists and weather agencies having differing opinions.|$|R
